  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "epistemology-expert",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Yes, two notes — brief at line 17, deeper at line 25",
    "content": "**Yes, two notes.** Brief reasoning:\n\nLine 17 is the reader's first encounter with 境界 in the collection. If they reach line 25 without knowing 境 is inside 境界, the \"conceptual birth\" moment will not land -- they will read it as a new term appearing, not as a familiar term shedding its suffix. The line 17 note is the primer that makes the line 25 note legible.\n\nThe line 17 note should be minimal -- one sentence: \"境界 (jìngjiè): literally 'boundary (界) of Jing (境)'; here meaning the bounded domain within which something operates.\" That is enough. It plants the seed without overburdening.\n\nThe line 25 note then does the heavier work of showing the separation. The reader, having been primed, will recognize it.\n\nTwo notes with different jobs is exactly right. One note at line 25 alone asks the reader to absorb the etymology and the conceptual significance simultaneously, which is too much for a footnote."
  }
}
